THE RISK (context, do not rewrite): perturbation [{"nodeId":"obtainableFactor","op":"set","value":0.008,"note":"Year-1 capture when pipeline is concentrated in qualification-gated large accounts; below the model's 0.01 band floor"}], likelihood 0.6, category execution

FIELDS TO REWRITE:
{
 "title": "Year-1 obtainable is correlated with the slowest cell: large-operator qualification cycles push real Year-1 capture an order of magnitude below 3%",
 "narrative": "The 3% obtainable factor comes from generic SOM benchmarks that assume Year-1 capture is drawn evenly from the SAM. But the venture has declared it will concentrate Year-1 effort on large operators — precisely the buyer cell with the longest procurement cycle: AVL qualification, certification review, pilot deployment, framework negotiation, typically longer than the entire 12-month horizon. The funnel treats obtainable pace and buyer mix as independent; the venture's own GTM choice makes them strongly negatively correlated. The hardware-entrant analogues the corpus surfaced (worked examples at ~0.1% of SAM, real entrants starting near 0.001%) all point the same direction: a pre-launch entrant selling into qualification-gated accounts books close to nothing in year one, whatever the market size says.",
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "The declared GTM concentrates Year-1 pipeline in large operators at pre-launch stage — accounts held by incumbents with named global relationships (Vertiv's customer list) and formal vendor-qualification gates",
   "refs": [
    "profile:Who is the primary buyer you'll sell through first?",
    "profile:Stage",
    "digest:cust-mix#c9"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "The 3% is anchored on generic early-stage SOM benchmarks (1–5%) with no DC-hardware specificity, and its own cross-check history shows the prior 6% was already revised down once; nothing in the benchmark reflects qualification-cycle length in the chosen buyer cell",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:obtainableFactor",
    "ledger:cust.operator-large"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "Obtainable pace is a function of the buyer cell it is applied to; concentrated on the slowest cell, the effective Year-1 factor sits far below the 0.01 low band edge, and YAM overstates first-year revenue by roughly an order of magnitude",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:obtainableFactor",
    "digest:cust-mix#c0"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "'Conservative ramp' was explicitly selected and the factor was already revised down from 6% to 3% — the box looks double-checked. What the revision didn't touch is the correlation: the same profile that set the pace assumption also set the buyer target, and the two choices interact multiplicatively in a funnel that models them as independent sliders.",
 "falsifier": "A documented case of a new rack-PDU entrant (or comparable DC hardware entrant) closing ≥3% of a regional SAM within 12 months selling direct to large operators — or the venture's own first RFQ-to-PO completing in under 6 months at a large account.",
 "likelihoodRationale": "Multiple independent benchmark critiques in the corpus (multi-year SOM windows, hardware entrants at 0.001–0.1% of SAM) plus documented incumbent lock at large accounts all point below the 1% band floor for this specific buyer strategy. [evidence revision: Two mechanism premises are corroborated by independent sources: DC-hardware AVL/RVL qualification gates are real and formal, and standard SOM practice ties obtainable capture to sales-cycle length and buyer mix (not a flat percentage). This strengthens the directional claim that concentrating on the slowest, qualification-gated cell depresses Year-1 capture. Offsetting this, the benchmark evidence shows 3% is conventionally a Year-2 figure with 1% for Year-1, which slightly recalibrates the 'order of magnitude below 3%' framing, and no falsifying counterexample was found but also no direct rack-PDU quantitative case confirming the ~0.001% floor. Net effect is neutral, so the prior 0.6 holds.]"
}

